         <abstract>
            <p>Small economic units such as individuals or micro-enterprises often face serious difficulties in obtaining credit in poor countries. Microcredit, which refers to the provision of credit to such units, is becoming an important policy tool for economic development. We examine the various conceptual issues associated with microcredit. In particular, we focus on the concept of group-based lending and the experiences of the Grameen Bank in Bangladesh. We conclude by assessing the potential long-term contribution of group-based lending and microcredit to development and growth.</p>
         </abstract>
